# TypeScript type imports

- **Always use `import type { ... }`** for TypeScript-only symbols (interfaces, type aliases, type-only enums).
- **Never mix `type` inside normal import blocks.** Do not use inline `type` (e.g. `import { type Foo, bar }` or `import { Foo, type Bar }`).

Use two separate statements: one for types, one for values.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD – type mixed with value import
import { type UserDto, getUsers } from './api';

// ❌ BAD – types in value import block
import { UserDto, getUsers } from './api';

// ✅ GOOD – type-only import and value import separate
import type { UserDto } from './api';
import { getUsers } from './api';
```

When a file only needs types from a module, use a single type-only import:

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD
import type { UserDto, ApiResponse } from './api';
```
